        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We use a standard set-up for continuum observations in Band-7: 4 basebands in FDM with a bandwidth of 1.875 GHz and a spectral resolution of ~27 km/s. 

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We ask for a 0.2"  angular resolution to match the size of the bright star-forming blobs observed in the SINFONI narrow Ha map (Fig. 2). The largest angular structure is set to 2" since this is the extension of the host galaxy in the 3"x3" of the SINFONI field-of-view.

</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>From the SFR value, 100 Msun/yr, measured with the narrow Ha emission (Fig. 2), we 
have derived the total infrared luminosity (LIR) in the 8-1000micron range using the 
relation from Kennicutt et al. (1998). After converting the luminosity to the flux
at the redshift of the quasar, we have used it to normalize a library
of 64 templates from Dale &amp; Helou (2001). For each one of these
normalized templates we can estimate the flux at 260 micron. We will use
the median value as our best estimate of the band 7 continuum flux
density: S(260 micron)=0.62 mJy

From the SINFONI observations we measured that ~80% of the total star-formation is concentrated in four blobs (Fig. 2). We have then used a value of S(260 micron rest-frame)=0.62*0.8/4~0.124 mJy as our estimate of the expected continuum flux in one of these blobs. The angular resolution selected for these observations, 0.2", matches the size of the blobs observed in the SINFONI map.

The requested sensitivity of 24.8 microJy will return a detection of the continuum in the blobs with a S/N of 5 over an aggregated bandwidth of 7.5 GHz.

We have also considered the possibility to observe in band 6: from the
SED we predicted a flux density S(380 micron rest-frame)=0.37 mJy,
which translates in an expected flux in on of the blobs of 0.074
mJy. The total integration time for a 0.2'' resolution to obtain a
S/N=5 (rms=14.8 microJy) amounts to 3.31 hours. 
Observing in Band-7 has therefore the advantages to require 
~40% less integration time and to probe wavelengths close to the infrared SED peak.

These observations will secure a high signal to noise map of the star-forming regions in the host galaxy.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
