    <prp:abstract>Theoretical models of AGN radiative feedback predict that AGN-driven, galaxy wide massive outflows
are not a rare and peculiar phenomenon, but a fundamental process affecting the bulk of the baryons 
in the Universe. While there are observational evidences that AGN outflows are common, more 
challenging is to demonstrate the impact that they have on the host galaxy ISM and star-formation. 

SINFONI/VLT observations of a QSO at z~2.4 (Cano-Diaz et al. 2012) shows a clear anti-correlation 
between the presence of strong outflow  (traced by the wing of the [OIII] line) and star-formation 
(traced by narrow Halpha emission).

We propose to use ALMA to map the star formation in the host galaxy of this QSO as traced by heated 
dust (continuum at 260 micron rest-frame in band 7) with kpc scale resolution. We will then be 
sensitive to regions of obscured star-formation that are opaque in the narrow Halpha SINFONI map.

This pilot project will allow us to test one of the best observational evidence of AGN radiative
feedback currently available.


</prp:abstract>
